               <interp inst="t18440205-741" type="uri" value="sessionsPapers/18440205"></interp>
               <interp inst="t18440205-741" type="date" value="18440205"></interp>
               <join result="criminalCharge" id="t18440205-741-charge-1" targOrder="Y" targets="def1-741-18440205 t18440205-741-offence-1 t18440205-741-verdict-1"></join>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184402050172"></xptr>
               <p>741. <persName id="def1-741-18440205" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def1-741-18440205" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-741-18440205" type="surname" value="JEFFRIES"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-741-18440205" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">WILLIAM JEFFRIES</hi>
                  </persName> was indicted<rs id="t18440205-741-offence-1" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18440205-741-offence-1" type="offenceCategory" value="theft"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18440205-741-offence-1" type="offenceSubcategory" value="stealingFromMaster"></interp> for stealing 6 sheets of printed paper, value 2<hi rend="italic">d</hi>.; 7 sheets of paper, 2<hi rend="italic">d</hi>.; 23 printed books, 2<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.; half-a-pint of ink, 6<hi rend="italic">d</hi>.; 4 hanks of twine, 6<hi rend="italic">d</hi>.; 2 packets of stove-paste, 1<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.; 2 boxes of tooth-powder, 6<hi rend="italic">d</hi>.; and 5 book-binders' tools, called letters, value 6<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.; the goods of <persName id="t18440205-name-1185" type="victimName">
                        <interp inst="t18440205-name-1185" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440205-name-1185" type="surname" value="FORD"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440205-name-1185" type="given" value="GEORGE JOHN"></interp>
                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18440205-741-offence-1 t18440205-name-1185"></join>George John Ford</persName>, his master.</rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. DOANE</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">conducted the Prosecution.</hi>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18440205-name-1186" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18440205-name-1186" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440205-name-1186" type="surname" value="FORD"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440205-name-1186" type="given" value="GEORGE JOHN"></interp>GEORGE JOHN FORD</persName>
                  </hi>, <hi rend="italic">printer, Beech-street.</hi> The prisoner came into my service as shopman six or seven months ago—he continued till this day-week—having missed various kinds of property, I put myself in communica<lb></lb>tion with the police—I know these bookbinders' tools—this sheet of paper is printed for the express use of our office, and is of no use to any one else—it is used to find out the type, and no one else has any right to it—I know it by the impression of my own type on it—these small books were printed at our office—I know them by the type, and by the matter of them—here are fourteen—" The Way to Wealth," and "Advice to a Young Tradesman," by Franklin; and some of Pinnock's Catechisms—I know them by the dirt on them, and being in the office for a length of time—I never sold them—the prisoner had no right to take them—this is my bodkin, and is used in print<lb></lb>ing—he had no right to take it—here are some tools, called bookbinders' letters, belonging to a set—they are mine—here are two bottles of ink, which I know, and some twine, which was used in our business, and two packets of stove-paste—they are mine, and correspond in quality with what I missed—the paper I know from the soil, and from the damp; and two boxes of tooth<lb></lb>powder—I can speak to them all—I believe them to be mine—the whole are worth 10<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.—here are seven sheets of paper, such as we had.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. HORRT</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Are you a master printer? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes—some of these books bear my name—I am the publisher—we sell them in the trade at the rate of 9<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. a dozen—they have been printed, and have ben on sale some years—" The Way to Wealth" was never sold, because it was never pushed in the trade—I do not recollect selling any, except a few copies—I have never bought any of them—they have been in the trade—this other is the "Paraclete"—there were more of them sold—the other works were not printed by me—they are various sorts of religious tracts—I saw these only I few months since—this one is an odd number—this book, "Idle Jack Brown," was one of a set in the printing-office, and I missed it—the last time I recollect seeing it, was four or five months ago—I have four apprentices, two of them come from the parish—I have given the whole four a month's imprisonment for robbing me—Franklin is one of them—he is in my service now—I did not talk to him about being robbed—he came to me with another apprentice, and told me—he came and asked me to take him back, and it was in consequence of his communication, and promising to act properly, that I agreed to take him back—the prisoner has done work for my father and me—here are three impressions of this pattern paper found—I had a number thrown off—Franklin told me he was told by the prisoner to say that I fed him badly—he has complained about it—I fed him properly—I complained of his stopping away and neglecting his duty—there is nothing particular about the two bottles of ink—I know them—there is a label on the bottle, which was printed at our office—these tools and bodkin are like other tools used in the trade.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. DOANE</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Did you sell your own tools to the prisoner? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> No.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18440205-name-1187" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18440205-name-1187" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440205-name-1187" type="surname" value="FRANKLIN"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440205-name-1187" type="given" value="JOHN BENJAMIN"></interp>JOHN BENJAMIN FRANKLIN</persName>
                  </hi>. I am thirteen years old, and am apprenticed to the prosecutor—I have been so nearly four years. The prisoner came into his employ about seven months ago—I have fellow-apprentices—about.</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184402050173"></xptr>
               <p>eleven months ago we began making free with my matter's property—we went on when the prisoner was there—when he found us out he began-the same himself—Itook three quires of writing-paper out of the drawer, and gave it to him—he buttoned it up in his coat, and took it home—he knew it to be master's—he had some ink—he put the bottles into his pocket, and some stone-blue—I saw some books—I was up in the loop-hole of the office, cleaning it—I put the books out—the prisoner took them, and said they would do for him—he put them into his coat pocket, and took them away the same morning—I know these tools and letters—I did not know he had them—when he took them, I cannot tell—we used to steal every Tuesday, Thursday, and Saturday—he used to come in the morning and say, "I shall want some more of that paper I had before"—I had a month's imprisonment—my master took me back as I promised to be a good boy, and tell the truth.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> Was the writing-paper the first thing you saw hint take? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes—it is not here—the ink was the next thing—I oasnot say whether be took anything more that morning—the books were taken on quite's different day—I cannot say whether this box was taken on a different day to the ink and paper—there was ink, stone-blue, and paper take—I think the writing-paper and ink were taken at the same time, and the books were-all taken together—he took paper at different times—the prosecutor found out that we were robbing, but did not complain to us—I do not think he stopped me once when I was going to take something out—I cannot say whether he did or not—I do not think I begged forgiveness of him—I cannot recollect bis stopping and talking to me about wasting my master's property—it may. have happened—I used to threaten to tell Mr. Ford of this, and <hi rend="italic">Jem</hi> used to knock me about—I might have taken some books—I took a good many things—I told Mr. Ford every thing I took—I have never taken any books like these—I used to give all the paper and things that I took to Mr. Wright—he used to promise us things, and used to give us money—when the prisoner heard that we were taken, he got from my master's wife where we were taken to—he got home as soon as he could, and got all the things that were my master's as soon as be could, out of his house, because he waa frightened that we should tell.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. DOANE</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> When he stopped you thieving, did you go and tell your master? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> No.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18440205-name-1188" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18440205-name-1188" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440205-name-1188" type="surname" value="MANSFIELD"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440205-name-1188" type="given" value="STEPHEN"></interp>STEPHEN MANSFIELD</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">police-constable N</hi> 233.) I went to the prisoner's lodging, in Gray's Inn-lane, last Monday evening—I found him there, and told him I took him for robbing Mr. Ford—he said there was nothing there belonging to Mr. Ford, and we were at liberty to search—I searched, and found a basket by the side of his bed, and, in the basket, the property I have produced to-night—he said, the small books he bought at stalls, and the reft were Mr. Ford's</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> Upon your oath, were not the words he laid, that the small books he bought, and none of the others belonged to Mr. Ford? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> No</p>
               <p>
